ogy with a specialization in bacteriology. Learn more about career and education options here. Inside Bacteriology Bacteria are omnipresent microorganisms that can benefit or harm humans. Bacteriology is a subspecialty of microbiology, one of the biological sciences, and is most associated with the study of infectious diseases caused by microscopic bacteria. Bacteriologists study the structure, physiology, genetics and other characteristics of microscopic bacteria. Education Information There are many degree programs in the biological sciences, and you can also find microbiology programs that have bacteriology specializations. Individuals interested in the biological sciences need a solid foundation in mathematics, physics and chemistry. Students may pursue science-related career paths directly after receiving their undergraduate degree. They could also continue their education in graduate, medical, veterinary or other programs. Listed below are links to a few articles about degree programs in this field. Microbiology Programs Microbiology Master's Degree Microbiology Ph.D. Distance Learning Options Degrees in microbiology typically require a substantial amount of laboratory time. Therefore, online degree programs are rare. However, some associate's degree programs and courses in microbiology are available online. Review the links below for more information. Microbiology Online Bachelor's Program Online Microbiology Degrees Free Online Microbiology Courses Career Options With a bachelor's degree in microbiology, you may seek many entry-level lab positions with public health agencies, research institutions and private companies in the biomedical and biopharmaceutical industry. Individuals with a doctorate degree could seek independent research opportunities or university faculty appointments. Here is some more information about career options in the field of bacteriology. Bacteriologist Microbiologist Diagnostic Microbiologist Physician Biology Lab Careers Employment Outlook and Salary Information The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) reported that as of May 2013, microbiologists earned a median annual wage of $67,840. Biological technicians, who work in labs assisting scientists, had a median annual wage of $40,710. The BLS noted that employment of microbiologists was expected to grow slowly, specifically 7%, from 2012-2022. The number of biological technicians was predicted to rise at a slightly higher rate of 10%, while biological scientists were expected to see employment increases of 19% over the same decade, the BLS noted (www.bls.gov). Read more Bacteriology Related Articles RelatedRelated Articles Recently UpdatedRecent Articles PopularPopular Articles Become a Bacteriologist: Education and Career Roadmap Research the requirements to become a bacteriologist. Learn about the job description and read the step-by-step process to start a career... Schools with Microbiology Programs: How to Choose Microbiologists are biological scientists who study single-celled microbes and their interactions with other organisms. It's a broad... Bachelor of Science in Bio Medical Technology In Bachelor of Science in Biomedical Technology programs, students learn about applied biochemistry, advanced sciences and basic... Canvasser: Job Description, Duties and Salary Canvassers require little formal education. Learn about the education, job duties, and requirements of this career to see if this is the... Security Guard: Job Description, Duties and Salary Security guards require little formal education. Learn about the training, job duties and job requirements to see if this is the right... Physical Education Teacher: Job Description & Requirements Banquet Server: Job Description, Duties and Requirements Surgeon: Career Summary and Required Education Education Requirements for a General Contractor License Sales Associate: Job Description, Requirements and Career Information Sewing Classes Cincinnati There are two schools located within fi